04744nam a22005655i 9780226002873DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013033872  a9780226002873  a(DE-B1597)568076  a(OCoLC)1233041431  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aND1489b.K36 2014 4aND1489b.K36 2014 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a776223  aEC 87952rvk1 aKane, Carolyn L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChromatic Algorithms :bSynthetic Color, Computer Art, and Aesthetics after Code /cCarolyn L. Kane. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b114 color plates, 15 halftones, 3 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. How Color Became Code -- tPart 1. Chromatic Visions (400 B.C.–1969) -- t1. Colors Sacred and Synthetic -- t2. Synthetic Color in Video Synthesis -- tPart 2. Disciplining Color: Encounters with Number and Code (1965–1984) -- t3. Informatic Color and Aesthetic Transformations in Early Computer Art -- t4. Collaborative Computer Art and Experimental Color Systems -- t5. From Chromakey to the Alpha Channel -- tPart 3. “Transparent” Screens for Opaque Ontology (1984–2007) -- t6. Digital Infrared as Algorithmic Lifeworld -- t7. The Photoshop Cinema -- tPostscript. A New Dark Age -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese days, we take for granted that our computer screens—and even our phones—will show us images in vibrant full color. Digital color is a fundamental part of how we use our devices, but we never give a thought to how it is produced or how it came about. Chromatic Algorithms reveals the fascinating history behind digital color, tracing it from the work of a few brilliant computer scientists and experimentally minded artists in the late 1960s and early ‘70s through to its appearance in commercial software in the early 1990s. Mixing philosophy of technology, aesthetics, and media analysis, Carolyn Kane shows how revolutionary the earliest computer-generated colors were—built with the massive postwar number-crunching machines, these first examples of “computer art” were so fantastic that artists and computer scientists regarded them as psychedelic, even revolutionary, harbingers of a better future for humans and machines. But, Kane shows, the explosive growth of personal computing and its accompanying need for off-the-shelf software led to standardization and the gradual closing of the experimental field in which computer artists had thrived. Even so, the gap between the bright, bold presence of color onscreen and the increasing abstraction of its underlying code continues to lure artists and designers from a wide range of fields, and Kane draws on their work to pose fascinating questions about the relationships among art, code, science, and media in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny21st century. 0aArt and technology. 0aColor. 0aComputer art. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acolor, computer, technology, art, artwork, aesthetics, visual communication, visualization, digital, commercial software, history, historical, 20th century, computer-generated, machines, standardization, experimentation, modern, code, video, collaborative, photoshop, cinema, screens, changing expectations, transformation, psychedelic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226002873423Coveruhttps://www.d